1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,060
Why does Articulate exist?

2
00:00:05,060 --> 00:00:07,020
During my career as an architect,

3
00:00:07,020 --> 00:00:10,510
I've come to appreciate that
architecture is rarely constrained by

4
00:00:10,510 --> 00:00:16,040
technology alone. Most modern
technology is remarkably capable.

5
00:00:16,040 --> 00:00:18,970
Cloud platforms can scale globally.

6
00:00:18,970 --> 00:00:23,050
Frameworks are mature. Infrastructure
can be provisioned in minutes.

7
00:00:23,050 --> 00:00:25,280
AI can generate code,

8
00:00:25,390 --> 00:00:29,060
explain documentation and
automate many development tasks.

9
00:00:29,060 --> 00:00:31,510
Yet, with all these advances,

10
00:00:31,510 --> 00:00:34,245
one problem remains remarkably consistent.

11
00:00:34,245 --> 00:00:36,740
Understanding the architecture itself.

12
00:00:36,740 --> 00:00:39,990
Not the diagrams or the documentation,

13
00:00:39,990 --> 00:00:42,130
but the architecture.

14
00:00:42,130 --> 00:00:45,540
Regardless of the organisation,
industry or tech stack,

15
00:00:45,540 --> 00:00:50,360
architects spend a significant
proportion of their time trying to answer

16
00:00:50,360 --> 00:00:52,710
surprisingly simple questions, like:

17
00:00:52,710 --> 00:00:56,450
What does the current
architecture look like?

18
00:00:56,450 --> 00:01:00,400
Or why was it designed
like this? What changed?

19
00:01:00,400 --> 00:01:02,890
Can we trust the documentation?

20
00:01:02,890 --> 00:01:04,660
Who knows the answer?

21
00:01:04,660 --> 00:01:08,970
These questions rarely have
straightforward answers.

22
00:01:08,970 --> 00:01:13,700
This episode explores why I
believe that problem exists,

23
00:01:13,780 --> 00:01:16,770
why existing tools only solve part of it,

24
00:01:16,770 --> 00:01:20,200
and why I think recent advances in AI

25
00:01:20,200 --> 00:01:26,830
make it worth exploring
a different approach.

26
00:01:27,830 --> 00:01:32,795
One of the simplest definitions of
architecture is that it exists to enable

27
00:01:32,795 --> 00:01:36,440
change. Architects aren't
employed just to draw diagrams.

28
00:01:36,440 --> 00:01:41,870
They're employed to help organisations
make good decisions about change,

29
00:01:41,870 --> 00:01:47,770
like introducing new capabilities,
reducing risk, balancing trade-offs,

30
00:01:47,770 --> 00:01:49,400
managing tech debt,

31
00:01:49,720 --> 00:01:54,045
improving resilience and
supporting business strategy.

32
00:01:54,045 --> 00:01:59,890
Everything ultimately comes back to
understanding how today's architecture

33
00:01:59,890 --> 00:02:02,090
can safely evolve into tomorrow's.

34
00:02:02,090 --> 00:02:06,570
To do that requires
understanding the current state.

35
00:02:06,570 --> 00:02:10,300
Unfortunately, that is
often the hardest part.

36
00:02:10,300 --> 00:02:14,090
Architecture knowledge is
rarely found in one place.

37
00:02:14,090 --> 00:02:17,480
Instead, it's scattered
across the organisation.

38
00:02:17,480 --> 00:02:21,960
Some information lives in source
code or Infrastructure as Code,

39
00:02:21,960 --> 00:02:25,360
some in ADRs, in Confluence, diagrams,

40
00:02:25,360 --> 00:02:28,470
slide decks or monitoring systems.

41
00:02:28,490 --> 00:02:33,220
Some still exists in the memories of
people that have moved on years ago.

42
00:02:33,220 --> 00:02:36,630
Each source contains part of the truth.

43
00:02:36,930 --> 00:02:39,345
None contains the whole picture.

44
00:02:39,345 --> 00:02:43,960
Even worse, those sources
are continuously changing.

45
00:02:43,960 --> 00:02:46,850
Documentation slowly becomes outdated.

46
00:02:46,850 --> 00:02:50,170
Diagrams become disconnected from reality.

47
00:02:50,170 --> 00:02:53,440
Projects introduce new technologies.

48
00:02:53,440 --> 00:02:56,030
Teams change. Businesses evolve.

49
00:02:56,180 --> 00:03:03,170
The architecture moves while our
understanding slowly falls behind.

50
00:03:03,170 --> 00:03:05,920
This isn't the fault of architects.

51
00:03:05,920 --> 00:03:10,190
It's simply the consequence of
architecture being a living system rather

52
00:03:10,310 --> 00:03:11,990
than a static asset.

53
00:03:11,990 --> 00:03:15,875
The industry already has excellent tools.

54
00:03:15,875 --> 00:03:18,040
Confluence is good at documentation.

55
00:03:18,040 --> 00:03:20,955
Git is excellent at versioning files.

56
00:03:20,955 --> 00:03:24,980
Terraform manages infrastructure. Mermaid,

57
00:03:24,980 --> 00:03:28,335
PlantUML and C4 are
excellent at doing diagrams.

58
00:03:28,335 --> 00:03:32,875
Enterprise architecture management
platforms help organisations catalogue

59
00:03:32,875 --> 00:03:37,370
systems and relationships. The problem
is not that these tools are poor.

60
00:03:37,370 --> 00:03:40,970
The problem is that none of them
truly understand the architecture.

61
00:03:40,970 --> 00:03:44,310
Each tool represents one
projection of reality.

62
00:03:44,310 --> 00:03:48,460
A diagram is a view. An
ADR records a decision.

63
00:03:48,460 --> 00:03:51,430
Source code records implementation.

64
00:03:51,430 --> 00:03:54,130
Infrastructure describes a deployment.

65
00:03:54,130 --> 00:03:56,330
Documentation explains concepts.

66
00:03:56,330 --> 00:04:00,530
The architect is left connecting
those pieces together.

67
00:04:00,530 --> 00:04:05,700
In other words, the architecture
exists largely in people's heads.

68
00:04:05,700 --> 00:04:10,225
When architecture knowledge
becomes fragmented,

69
00:04:10,225 --> 00:04:13,930
every architectural activity
becomes more difficult.

70
00:04:13,930 --> 00:04:16,980
Understanding the current
state takes longer.

71
00:04:16,980 --> 00:04:21,850
Designs duplicate existing capabilities
because nobody knows what already

72
00:04:21,850 --> 00:04:26,850
exists. Architectural decisions
are forgotten and later repeated.

73
00:04:26,850 --> 00:04:30,450
Impact analysis becomes
a manual investigation.

74
00:04:30,450 --> 00:04:33,290
Documentation slowly loses relevance.

75
00:04:33,290 --> 00:04:36,400
Architects spend more time
searching for information

76
00:04:36,400 --> 00:04:39,080
than reasoning about solutions.

77
00:04:39,080 --> 00:04:42,540
None of these problems are
individually catastrophic.

78
00:04:42,540 --> 00:04:46,730
Collectively, they consume an
enormous amount of time and increase

79
00:04:46,730 --> 00:04:49,930
uncertainty across every project.

80
00:04:49,930 --> 00:04:54,160
So why now? Many of these
observations are not new.

81
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:56,490
I've been thinking about them for years.

82
00:04:56,490 --> 00:05:01,235
The difference is that now I believe
we finally have technology capable of

83
00:05:01,235 --> 00:05:06,315
helping. Large language models are
not only interesting because they can

84
00:05:06,315 --> 00:05:09,955
generate code. They are interesting
because they can reason across large

85
00:05:09,955 --> 00:05:14,925
collections of unstructured
information. They can identify patterns,

86
00:05:14,925 --> 00:05:19,610
summarise documents, highlight
contradictions, ask follow-up questions,

87
00:05:19,610 --> 00:05:23,830
extract structure, work
with incomplete evidence.

88
00:05:23,830 --> 00:05:28,530
None of these capabilities
replace architectural thinking.

89
00:05:28,530 --> 00:05:34,010
Instead, they augment it. That
changes the kind of tools we can

90
00:05:34,070 --> 00:05:36,490
realistically build. For the first time,

91
00:05:36,490 --> 00:05:42,270
it feels practical to imagine software
that helps architects understand

92
00:05:42,270 --> 00:05:45,880
architecture rather than
simply documenting it.

93
00:05:45,880 --> 00:05:51,770
So, the vision. Articulate began as a
side project to scratch my own itch.

94
00:05:51,770 --> 00:05:56,985
Like many personal projects,
it started small. An idea here,

95
00:05:56,985 --> 00:06:00,820
a prototype there, several
false starts, of course,

96
00:06:00,820 --> 00:06:05,100
more discarded ideas than
successful ones. Over time,

97
00:06:05,100 --> 00:06:08,550
those ideas converged into
a much broader question:

98
00:06:09,260 --> 00:06:15,160
Can architecture become a continuously
evolving body of knowledge instead of

99
00:06:15,160 --> 00:06:18,510
a collection of disconnected documents?

100
00:06:18,580 --> 00:06:22,390
That single question sits
at the heart of Articulate.

101
00:06:22,390 --> 00:06:24,555
It is not intended to replace architects,

102
00:06:24,555 --> 00:06:27,970
nor is it intended to generate
documentation automatically.

103
00:06:27,970 --> 00:06:31,500
Instead, it explores whether
AI can become

104
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:37,010
a genuine architectural collaborator,
helping architects to discover knowledge,

105
00:06:37,010 --> 00:06:40,550
challenge assumptions,
understand the trade-offs,

106
00:06:40,550 --> 00:06:44,850
maintain architectural
context, reason about change,

107
00:06:44,850 --> 00:06:48,830
preserve the decisions and continuously
improve their understanding of

108
00:06:48,830 --> 00:06:53,990
complex systems. Whether that proves
achievable remains to be seen.

109
00:06:53,990 --> 00:06:59,295
That uncertainty is exactly
why this project exists.

110
00:06:59,295 --> 00:07:05,780
One of the goals of this journal is
to avoid beginning with technology.

111
00:07:05,780 --> 00:07:11,020
Before discussing services,
databases, frameworks and AI models,

112
00:07:11,020 --> 00:07:13,500
I want to understand the
architectural principles

113
00:07:13,500 --> 00:07:17,350
that should shape the system.
Questions such as:

114
00:07:17,370 --> 00:07:21,410
What does it mean to version architecture?

115
00:07:21,410 --> 00:07:24,200
Can confidence be modelled?

116
00:07:24,200 --> 00:07:28,500
Should evidence become part
of the architectural model?

117
00:07:28,500 --> 00:07:31,320
Can conversations become
the primary interface?

118
00:07:31,320 --> 00:07:34,610
What role should AI
play in decision making?

119
00:07:34,610 --> 00:07:38,890
Where should humans
remain firmly in control?

120
00:07:38,890 --> 00:07:42,940
Answering these questions is more
important than selecting any particular

121
00:07:42,940 --> 00:07:46,260
technology stack. Technology will change.

122
00:07:46,260 --> 00:07:49,525
Principles should endure.

123
00:07:49,525 --> 00:07:51,565
If Articulate succeeds,

124
00:07:51,565 --> 00:07:55,400
I don't believe it will be because
it produces better diagrams or more

125
00:07:55,400 --> 00:07:59,720
documentation. It will succeed if
it helps architects spend less time

126
00:07:59,720 --> 00:08:04,070
searching for information and more
time solving meaningful problems.

127
00:08:04,070 --> 00:08:09,050
If it helps preserve architectural
knowledge, if it reduces uncertainty,

128
00:08:09,050 --> 00:08:12,210
if it encourages better
architectural conversations,

129
00:08:12,210 --> 00:08:14,500
if it helps explain the
consequences of change

130
00:08:14,500 --> 00:08:18,605
before those changes are implemented.
Most importantly,

131
00:08:18,605 --> 00:08:24,500
if it demonstrates that AI can become
a thoughtful architectural collaborator

132
00:08:24,500 --> 00:08:28,640
rather than simply another
code generation tool.

133
00:08:28,660 --> 00:08:30,360
So, looking ahead,

134
00:08:30,360 --> 00:08:34,920
this episode has intentionally
avoided discussing implementation.

135
00:08:34,920 --> 00:08:38,520
The purpose was to establish the
motivation behind the project.

136
00:08:38,590 --> 00:08:42,595
Future episodes will explore the
architectural principles, requirements,

137
00:08:42,595 --> 00:08:47,545
constraints and experiments that
will shape Articulate as it evolves.

138
00:08:47,545 --> 00:08:50,885
Some ideas will succeed. Some will fail.

139
00:08:50,885 --> 00:08:53,190
Many will change along the way.

140
00:08:53,340 --> 00:08:59,110
That is exactly what this journal
intends to document because, ultimately,

141
00:08:59,140 --> 00:09:02,490
Articulate is not about building software.

142
00:09:02,490 --> 00:09:06,535
It's an exploration into how we
might build better architecture.
